&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yes, while loops take boolean-like as arguments. By doing &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;while ($string_position = strpos($string, $find, $offset)) {
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;it first executes what is inside the parenthesis, then evaluates the result of that to determine if the loop should quit or not. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;strpos&lt;/code&gt; will return False if the needle was not found, so &lt;code&gt;$string_position&lt;/code&gt; will be false and as such the evaluation result will also be False and the loop will quit. If the needle is found, then loop continues after the attribution. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also it should be noted that &lt;code&gt;strpos&lt;/code&gt; might return a non-boolean that evaluates to False, so be careful with that construction.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://php.net/manual/en/function.strpos.php" rel="nofollow"&gt;Reference on strpos&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

